@node "Addbuffers"

ADDBUFFERS

FORMAT:         ADDBUFFERS [DRIVE=]<drive >:[[BUFFERS=]<n>]

TEMPLATES:      ADDBUFFERS [DRIVE=]<drive >:[[BUFFERS=]<n>]

PATH:           C:

Use:

The Amiga's floppy disk drive are not fast at the best of times; though
the situation has improved with the advent of FFS (Fast Filing System)
and directory catching. ADDBUFFERS allocates a small amount of RAM to act
as a sector cache or buffer.

EXAMPLES:-


        1>ADDBUFFERS DF0: 22 ; One track's worth of buffers

        1>ADDBUFFERS DF2: 1 ; NOT enough!



                                @{"     " link "commands"}  Return

@endnode

@node "Adddatatypes"
@toc "commands"

ADDDATATYPES

FORMAT:         ADDDATATYPES [[file=]{file|Pattern}] [QUIET] [REFRESH]

TEMPLATES:      FILE/M, QUIT/S, REFRESH/S

PATH:           C:



This command is primarily used by the system software - such as MultiView -
to add and read new datatypes.  Be  very  careful with this command it does
not generate any errors when faced with silly files!

Options:

FILE            The name of a new  datatype/types  may  be supplied here if
they are not already in the proper place - DEVS:Datatypes.
                You may want to use this  option if you have a floppy-based
system and wish to store the datatypes somewhere else.

QUIET/S         Don't generate any output.

REFRESH/S       Check the contents of  the  DEVS:Datatypes  drawer and make
any changes necessary. Only used when a new datatype has been added.


                                @{"     " link "commands"}  Return

@endnode

@node "Addmonitor"
@toc "commands"

ADDMONITOR

FORMAT:         ADDMONITOR [NAME=]<number> [NUMBER=]<name>[HBSTRT=<n>]
                [HBSTOP=<n>] [HSSTRT=<n>] [HSSTOP=<n>] [VBSTRT=<n>]
                [VBSTOP=<n>] [MINCOL=<n>] [TOTROWS=<n>] [TOTCLKS=<n>]
                [BEAMCONO=<N>]

TEMPLATES:      NUM/A/N, NAME/A, HBSTRT/K,  HBSTOP/K,  HSSTRT/K, HSSTOP/K
                VBSTRT/K, VBSTOP/K, VSSTRT/K, VSSTOP/K, MINROW/K, MINCOL/K,
                TOTROWS/K, TOTCLKS/K, BEAMCON0/K

PATH:           SYS:SYSTEM/


This command is used to connect  non-standard  displays to the Amiga system
and to alter the private  hardware  register settings for special displays.
New monitors can be added  during  boot  by  dragging  their icons into the
Monitors drawer: alternatively, you can  use  this command directly to make
the changes. Once done, you must  use  the ScreenMode (Preferences) tool to
change to the appropriate  display.  Under  normal  circumstances, only the
first two such as video effects units. The keywords detailed write directly
into hardware  registers  and  should  be  used  with  extreme  caution, or
preferably, not at all.

New AmigaDos 2.1+

From this release ADDMONITOR and  its  associated commands, BINDMONITOR are
replaced by separate  monitor  commands,  located  in DEVS:monitors drawer.
Options, Except NAME and NUM are as detailed here.

Options:

NAME/A          The name assigned to  that  monitor:  NTSC, PAL, Multiscan,
A2024.

EXAMPLE:

                        Addmonitor NUM=2 NAME=Pal

NUM/A/M         The number assigned to the monitor type from 1 to 4.
                Example:

                        AddMonitor NUM=3 NAME=Multiscan



                                @{"     " link "commands"}  Return

@endnode

